      <body>
         <div type="entry">
                <head>Zacharias, Pseudo-</head>
                <ab type="idnos">
                    <idno type="URI">https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Zacharias-Pseudo-</idno>
                    <idno type="syriaca-bibl">http://syriaca.org/bibl/627</idno>
                    <idno type="entry">618</idno>
                    <milestone unit="pages" n="448"/>
                    <idno type="althead" subtype="altorder">Pseudo- Zacharias</idno>
                    <note type="type">pseudonym</note>
                    <note type="abstract">A 6th-cent. anonymous <abbr>Syr. Orth.</abbr> author, possibly a monk,
                        who compiled a variety of sources into a chronicle in Syriac, including the
                        6th-cent. Ecclesiastical History of Zacharias Rhetor.<note/>
                    </note>
                </ab>
                <div type="body">
                    <p>A 6th-cent. anonymous <abbr>Syr. Orth.</abbr> author, possibly a monk, who compiled a
                        variety of sources into a chronicle in Syriac, including the 6th-cent.
                        Ecclesiastical History of <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Zacharias-Rhetor">
                            <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/58">Zacharias
                            Rhetor</persName>
                        </ref> 
                  <abbr>bp.</abbr> of Mitylene, who died after 536. Books I–II of
                        Pseudo-Zacharias <choice>
                            <sic>includes</sic>
                            <corr>include</corr>
                        </choice> among others the history of Joseph and Aseneth,
                        the Acts of St. Silvester of Rome, and the Legend of the <ref rend="bold"
                       target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Sleepers-of-Ephesus-Legend-of-the">Sleepers of Ephesus</ref>. Books III–VI contain the Syriac translation
                        of the Ecclesiastical History by Zacharias Rhetor. The reigns of Anastasius
                        and Justin I are the subjects of Parts VII–VIII, while the reign of
                        Justinian and Justin II up to the year 569 are the subjects of Parts IX–XII.
                        The rest of the Chronicle to Book XII is fragmentary. The importance of this
                        document resides in the fact that it deals with the later 5th and 6th <abbr>cent.</abbr>,
                        a time of intense christological controversies that divided Christianity
                        into several denominations.</p>
                </div>
